Appendix 8
Vafthrudnismal 35 is rendered by Gering: &ldquo;Ungezählte Winter vor der Schöpfung / geschah Bergelmirs Geburt. / Als frühestes weiss ich, dass der erfahrene Riese / Im Boote geborgen ward.&rdquo; Simrock translates similarly, and he remarks (Hdb. Dt. Myth., § 9): &ldquo;Das dunkle Wort ludr für Boot zu nehmen, sind wir sowohl durch den Zusammenhang als durch die Mythenvergleichung berechtigt.&rdquo;
R. B. Anderson (The Younger Edda [1880], pp. 60f.) translates the verse — quoted by Snorri (Gylf.

Appendix 14
The name Mundilfoeri (Mundel-fere) raises a cluster of problems, and nothing is gained by evasive statements such as that given by de Vries (Altnord. Etym. Wb., p. 395): &ldquo;Mundilferi. Name of the father of the Moon . . . Mundill. Name of a legendary figure.&rdquo;
As concerns mund, feminine, it means &ldquo;hand&rdquo; (Cleasby-Vigfusson, s.v.), but mund comprises the meaning of tutelage, guardianship (cf. German Vormund). Mund as a neutrum means &ldquo;point of time, mood, humor, measure, and the right time&rdquo; (de Vries, loc.

